 The purpose of the new line is to allow regional and express trains to run directly between <unk> Station , <unk> Station and <unk> Station , without being slowed and delayed by commuter trains that make frequent stops at intermediate stations . The <unk> Line will improve <unk> , and capacity will increase from 12 to 26 trains per hour in each direction . Travel time from <unk> to <unk> Station will be reduced from 20 to 13 minutes . The line has received criticism for not being a true high @-@ speed line , and for <unk> Station not being in compliance with accessibility requirements . Similar parallel , high @-@ speed lines have been or will be built northeast and southeast of Oslo . 
 Following the construction of the high @-@ speed Gardermoen Line from Oslo , via Oslo Airport , Gardermoen , to <unk> , the Norwegian Ministry of Transport and Communications started planning additional high @-@ speed lines west and southeast of Oslo . The <unk> and <unk> Lines would allow express and regional trains to travel faster and more reliably to <unk> and <unk> , leaving the old tracks for slower freight trains , and commuter trains making frequent stops . Construction of the <unk> Line will , at the earliest , be completed in 2015 . 
 The Gardermoen Line had shown that profits could be made by operating passenger trains , but that it would not be possible to debt @-@ finance short @-@ distance tracks in Eastern Norway . Therefore , a conventional financial method for the <unk> Line was started . While the railway is entirely financed through allocation through the state budget , the <unk> was secured through a political compromise for investments in Greater Oslo , the Oslo <unk> 2 . <unk> of a diverse range of road and public transport investments — including new <unk> , extension of the Oslo Metro and new railways — would be made through a " package " . This involved both state , county and toll funding being collected in one lot , and then <unk> the funds to the agencies responsible for the investments . 
 Prior to the construction , the Western Corridor had a capacity of 12 – 14 trains per hour in each direction west of <unk> . The first section of the <unk> Line , from <unk> to <unk> , increased the capacity with an additional two trains . The opening of <unk> Station will increase capacity with four more , since all stations along the line between Oslo and <unk> will then have four platforms . When the whole line is completed , total capacity in the Western Corridor will be 26 trains per hour . This is equivalent to 5 @,@ 500 cars per hour , and exceeds the capacity of a four @-@ lane motorway . 
 The <unk> Line is also a necessary component to allow a high @-@ speed route to be built along the <unk> and <unk> Lines . The former is planned to branch off at <unk> , while the latter would branch of at <unk> , and become a 60 @-@ kilometre ( 37 mi ) <unk> of the Bergen Line . The first sections of the upgraded <unk> Line opened in 1995 and 2001 , and additional proposals are under planning for the remaining sections . 
 <unk> Station is 14 @.@ 14 km ( 8 @.@ 79 mi ) from Oslo S , at 12 @.@ 0 metres ( 39 @.@ 4 ft ) elevation . The track layout has been criticised by among others Norsk <unk> , for not permitting high through speeds . A sharp curve before the station will not permit trains to travel at more than 80 km / h ( 50 mph ) , even if they are not scheduled to stop at the station . This will increase travel time , and hinder the efficiency of the line should it be used later for high @-@ speed lines to <unk> or Western Norway . The proposed <unk> Line would <unk> just west of <unk> Station . 
 Construction of the second section started in 2007 and was completed in 2011 . The section between <unk> and <unk> is 6 @.@ 7 kilometres ( 4 @.@ 2 mi ) , most of which runs through the 5 @.@ 5 @-@ kilometre ( 3 @.@ 4 mi ) <unk> Tunnel . There was local debate whether the tunnel should be built using a tunnel boring machine or by drilling and blasting . The latter was preferred by the Rail Administration , since it allowed a shorter construction time , and a NOK 700 million saving . Total budget is NOK 2 @,@ 787 million . 
 <unk> Station serves as the main public transport hub for Eastern <unk> , parts of Western Oslo and Fornebu . Within 800 metres ( 2 @,@ 600 ft ) , there are 20 @,@ 000 jobs , with an additional 10 – 15 @,@ 000 in development . Located 7 @.@ 00 kilometres ( 4 @.@ 35 mi ) west of Oslo S , it is receiving a major overhaul between 2006 and 2009 , including 1 @.@ 2 km ( 0 @.@ 75 mi ) of new track . The current station will be entirely replaced , and the number of platforms increased from two to four . More than one thousand buses depart from <unk> Station each day , and it has been proposed as the terminus of the Fornebu Line — a <unk> originally proposed as a people <unk> . 
 The NOK 1 billion renovation has become a scandal , due to the station being built in a curve , and thus does not have straight platforms . This will become a security problem ; in addition it will create a gap up to 40 centimetres ( 16 in ) between the train and the platform , hindering accessibility to the trains for disabled people . Norges <unk> claims they will have to buy new trains due to this station alone , costing the state @-@ owned company NOK 1 @.@ 5 billion . Minister of Transport , <unk> <unk> <unk> from the Centre Party , has said that resolving the problems by building a straight station is not an alternative , since it would cost an additional hundred @-@ millions of NOK , and delay the new station several years . 
 The last section is a proposed 2 @.@ 1 @-@ kilometre ( 1 @.@ 3 mi ) section from <unk> to <unk> ; the latter not being modified as part of the extension , since it was upgraded in 1999 . The government has not set a date to start construction , but it will not be until at least <unk> , since other projects will be <unk> over this section . No specific route has been finalised , and the project has been proposed to either run parallel to the current <unk> Line , or by placing all four tracks through a new tunnel . The former has been preferred by the Rail Administration , while the latter — which would cost NOK 1 billion more — has been preferred by the municipality . There are no intermediate commuter stations between <unk> and <unk> , so there is little <unk> or speed potential to gain from the construction , since the Oslo Tunnel from <unk> to Oslo Central Station will still remain a bottleneck with only two tracks . <unk> have claimed that there is no gain from building this section without building two additional tracks all the way to the central station . 
