 During the summers of the mid @-@ 20th century , parents in the US and Europe <unk> the annual appearance of <unk> ( or <unk> ) , which was commonly known as " <unk> <unk> " . The disease was rare at the beginning of the century , and worldwide there were only a few thousand cases per year , but by the 1950s there were 60 @,@ 000 cases each year in the US alone and an average of 2 @,@ 300 in England and Wales . 
 During 1916 and 1917 there had been a major epidemic in the US ; 27 @,@ 000 cases and 6 @,@ 000 deaths were recorded , with 9 @,@ 000 cases in New York City . At the time nobody knew how the virus was spreading . Many of the city 's inhabitants , including scientists , thought that impoverished <unk> @-@ dwelling immigrants were to blame even though the prevalence of the disease was higher in the more prosperous districts such as <unk> Island – a pattern that had also been seen in cities like Philadelphia . Many other <unk> countries were affected at the same time . In particular , before the outbreaks in the US , large <unk> had occurred in Sweden . 
 The reason for the rise of <unk> in <unk> countries in the 20th century has never been fully explained . The disease is caused by a virus that is passed from person to person by the <unk> @-@ oral route , and naturally <unk> only humans . It is a paradox that it became a problem during times of improved sanitation and increasing <unk> . Although the virus was discovered at the beginning of the 20th century , its <unk> was <unk> until the 1950s . It is now known that fewer than two per cent of individuals who are infected develop the disease , and most infections are mild . During <unk> the virus was effectively everywhere , which explains why public health officials were unable to isolate a source . 
 Following the development of <unk> in the mid @-@ 1950s , mass <unk> campaigns took place in many countries . In the US , after a campaign promoted by the March of <unk> , the annual number of <unk> cases fell dramatically ; the last outbreak was in 1979 . In 1988 the World Health Organisation along with others launched the Global <unk> <unk> Initiative , and by 1994 the Americas were declared to be free of disease , followed by the Pacific region in 2000 and Europe in 2003 . At the end of 2012 , only 223 cases were reported by the World Health Organisation . <unk> <unk> type 1 infections , 122 occurred in Nigeria , one in Chad , 58 in Pakistan and 37 in Afghanistan . <unk> teams often face danger ; seven <unk> were murdered in Pakistan and nine in Nigeria at the beginning of 2013 . In Pakistan , the campaign was further hampered by the murder on 26 February 2013 of a police officer who was providing security . 
 The human <unk> virus ( HIV ) is the virus that – when the infection is not treated – can cause AIDS ( acquired <unk> syndrome ) . Most <unk> believe that HIV originated in sub @-@ Saharan Africa during the 20th century , and over 70 million individuals have been infected by the virus . By 2011 , an estimated 35 million had died from AIDS , making it one of the most destructive <unk> in recorded history . HIV @-@ 1 is one of the most significant viruses to have emerged in the last quarter of the 20th century . When , in 1981 , a scientific article was published that reported the deaths of five young gay men , no one knew that they had died from AIDS . The full scale of the epidemic – and that the virus had been silently emerging over several decades – was not known . 
 HIV crossed the species barrier between <unk> and humans in Africa in the early decades of the 20th century . During the years that followed there were enormous social changes and turmoil in Africa . Population shifts were unprecedented as vast numbers of people moved from rural farms to the expanding cities , and the virus was spread from remote regions to densely populated urban <unk> . The incubation period for AIDS is around 10 years , so a global epidemic starting in the early 1980s is credible . At this time there was much <unk> and <unk> . The " out of Africa " theory for the origin of the HIV pandemic was not well received by Africans , who felt that the " blame " was <unk> . This led the World Health Assembly to pass a 1987 resolution , which stated that HIV is " a naturally occurring [ virus ] of undetermined geographic origin " . 
 The HIV pandemic has challenged communities and brought about social changes throughout the world . Opinions on sexuality are more openly discussed . <unk> on sexual practices and drug use – which were once taboo – is sponsored by many governments and their healthcare providers . <unk> on the ethics of provision and cost of anti @-@ <unk> drugs , particularly in poorer countries , have highlighted <unk> in healthcare and stimulated far @-@ reaching legislative changes . In developing countries the impact of HIV / AIDS has been profound ; key organisations such as healthcare , defense and civil services have been severely disrupted . Life expectancy has fallen . In Zimbabwe , for example , life expectancy was 79 years in 1991 but by 2001 it had fallen to 39 years . 
 When influenza virus undergoes a genetic shift many humans have no immunity to the new strain , and if the population of susceptible individuals is high enough to maintain the chain of infection , <unk> occur . The genetic changes usually happen when different strains of the virus co @-@ infect animals , particularly birds and <unk> . Although many viruses of vertebrates are restricted to one species , influenza virus is an exception . The last pandemic of the 19th century occurred in 1899 and resulted in the deaths of 250 @,@ 000 people in Europe . The virus , which originated in Russia or Asia , was the first to be rapidly spread by people on trains and <unk> . 
 A new strain of the virus emerged in 1918 , and the subsequent pandemic of Spanish flu was one of the worst natural disasters in history . The death toll was enormous ; throughout the world around 50 million people died from the infection . There were 550 @,@ 000 reported deaths caused by the disease in the US , ten times the country 's losses during the First World War , and 228 @,@ 000 deaths in the UK . In India there were more than 20 million deaths , and in Western Samoa 22 per cent of the population died . Although cases of influenza occurred every winter , there were only two other <unk> in the 20th century . 
 In 1957 another new strain of the virus emerged and caused a pandemic of Asian flu ; although the virus was not as <unk> as the 1918 strain , over one million died worldwide . The next pandemic occurred when Hong Kong flu emerged in 1968 , a new strain of the virus that replaced the 1957 strain . <unk> mainly the elderly , the 1968 pandemic was the least severe , but 33 @,@ 800 were killed in the US . New strains of influenza virus often originate in East Asia ; in rural China the concentration of ducks , pigs , and humans in close proximity is the highest in the world . 
 The most recent pandemic occurred in 2009 , but none of the last three has caused anything near the devastation seen in 1918 . <unk> why the strain of influenza that emerged in 1918 was so devastating is a question that still remains <unk> . 
 <unk> are viruses that are transmitted to humans and other vertebrates by blood @-@ sucking insects . These viruses are diverse ; the term " <unk> " – which was derived from " <unk> @-@ borne virus " – is no longer used in formal taxonomy because many species of virus are known to be spread in this way . There are more than 500 species of <unk> , but in the 1930s only three were known to cause disease in humans : yellow fever virus , <unk> virus and <unk> fever virus . More than 100 of such viruses are now known to cause human diseases including <unk> . 
 Yellow fever is the most notorious disease caused by a <unk> . The last major epidemic in the US occurred in 1905 . During the building of the Panama Canal thousands of workers died from the disease . Yellow fever originated in Africa and the virus was brought to the Americas on cargo ships , which were <unk> the <unk> <unk> <unk> that carries the virus . The first recorded epidemic in Africa occurred in Ghana , in West Africa , in 1926 . In the 1930s the disease re @-@ emerged in Brazil . Fred <unk> , an American <unk> ( 1893 – 1977 ) , discovered the importance of the sylvatic cycle of infection in non @-@ human hosts , and that infection of humans was a " dead end " that broke this cycle . Although the yellow fever vaccine is one of the most successful ever developed , <unk> continue to occur . In 1986 – 91 in West Africa , over 20 @,@ 000 people were infected , 4 @,@ 000 of whom died . 
