 The <unk> virus epidemic in West Africa , which began in 2013 , is the most devastating since the emergence of HIV . The initial outbreak occurred in December 2013 in <unk> , a village in southern Guinea . Among the first victims were a two @-@ year @-@ old boy , his three @-@ year @-@ old sister , their mother and grandmother . After the grandmother 's funeral , which was attended by her family and <unk> , the disease spread to neighbouring villages . By March 2014 the outbreak was severe enough to raise the concern of local health officials who reported it to the <unk> Ministry of Health . By the middle of the year the epidemic had spread to <unk> and Sierra Leone . As of June <unk> , the World Health Organisation reported over 27 @,@ 000 cases of the disease , which had resulted in more than 11 @,@ 000 deaths . 
 The natural source of <unk> virus is probably bats . <unk> viruses are transmitted to humans by monkeys , and <unk> fever by rats ( <unk> <unk> ) . <unk> infections can be severe because humans often have no natural resistance to the infection and it is only when viruses become well @-@ adapted to new host that their <unk> decreases . Some <unk> infections are often " dead ends " , in that after the initial outbreak the rate of subsequent infections <unk> because the viruses are not efficient at spreading from person to person . 
