 Marshal of the Royal Air Force Cyril Louis Norton <unk> , 1st Baron <unk> <unk> , <unk> , <unk> , CBE , AM ( 15 February 1886 – 30 November 1963 ) was a senior officer of the British Army and Royal Air Force . He commanded units of the Royal Flying Corps and Royal Air Force in the First World War , and served as Chief of the Air Staff during the first years of the Second World War . From 1941 to 1946 he was the Governor @-@ General of New Zealand . 
 Born to a military family , <unk> studied at the Royal Military College , <unk> , before taking a commission as a junior officer in the Royal Warwickshire Regiment in 1905 . After transferring to the 2nd <unk> Rifles in the Indian Army , he saw active service on the North West Frontier , but after learning to fly in 1911 turned towards a career in military aviation . During the First World War he rose from flying instructor to command of 41st Wing RFC , the main strategic bombing force , and was awarded the Albert Medal for putting out a fire in an explosives store . 
 He served in staff positions through the 1920s and was Air Officer Commanding the Middle East Command in the early 1930s before becoming Air Member for Supply and Organisation in 1935 . <unk> was appointed Chief of the Air Staff in 1937 and , in that role , supported sharp increases in aircraft production , increasing expenditure on the new , heavily armed , Hurricane and Spitfire fighters , essential to re @-@ equip Fighter Command . However , he was sacked after the Battle of Britain after political intrigue caused him to lose Churchill 's confidence . In 1941 he was appointed Governor @-@ General of New Zealand , holding office until 1946 . 
 <unk> began to turn towards a career in aviation in 1911 , when he learned to fly in a Bristol <unk> at <unk> whilst on leave in England . He held certificate No. 144 issued by the Royal Aero Club . He later passed a formal course at the Central Flying School , <unk> in 1913 , and began working as a pilot trainer there from 17 November 1913 ; it was intended that he would form part of a flight training school to be established in India , but he had not yet left England when the First World War broke out . 
 On the outbreak of war , <unk> was in England . On 12 September 1914 , he was given the temporary rank of captain , and attached to the Royal Flying Corps as a flight commander , to serve with No. 1 Squadron on the Western Front . He was promoted to the permanent rank of captain on 22 September , effective from 16 August . On 24 March 1915 he was promoted to major and appointed to command No. 12 Squadron , flying <unk> aircraft in France from September onwards . The squadron took part in the Battle of <unk> , bombing railways and carrying out reconnaissance missions in October 1915 . 
 On taking command of the squadron , he chose to stop flying personally in order to concentrate on administration , a decision which was regarded <unk> by his men ; relations were strained until January 1916 , when he demonstrated his courage by walking into a burning bomb store to try to control the fire . He was awarded the Albert Medal for this act on the personal recommendation of General Hugh Trenchard , and in February 1916 was promoted to lieutenant colonel and given command of Training No. 6 Wing in England . In December 1916 he took command of No. 9 Wing in France , a long @-@ range bomber and reconnaissance formation , and in October 1917 took command of the newly formed No. 41 Wing . This was upgraded as the 8th Brigade in December , with <unk> promoted accordingly to the temporary rank of brigadier @-@ general on 28 December 1917 . During 1918 , it joined the Independent <unk> Force , which was the main strategic bombing arm of the newly formed Royal Air Force . In June 1918 <unk> was appointed the Deputy Commander of the Independent <unk> Force , serving under Trenchard . 
 <unk> was awarded the Croix d <unk> of the French Legion of Honour on 10 October 1918 , and appointed a Companion of the Order of St Michael and St George on 1 January 1919 , a Commander of the Order of the British Empire on 3 June 1919 and an Officer of the Belgian Order of Leopold on 18 April 1921 . 
 <unk> was granted a permanent commission in the Royal Air Force as a lieutenant colonel on 1 August 1919 and promoted to group captain on 8 August 1919 . He became Deputy Director of Personnel at the Air Ministry in August 1919 and then Deputy Commandant of the <unk> ' technical training school in August 1922 . He married May <unk> in 1922 ; she died in September 1924 , and he remarried the following year to Olive Foster , an American woman . He had three children with Foster , a son and two daughters . 
 <unk> was promoted to air <unk> on 1 January 1925 , and took command of the newly formed <unk> Air Force in May 1925 . He was appointed to a League of Nations <unk> committee in December 1925 and then became Deputy Chief of the Air Staff and Director of Operations and Intelligence on 12 April 1926 . He was appointed a Companion of the Order of the Bath in the 1929 <unk> Honours and , having been promoted to air vice marshal on 1 January 1930 , he stood down as Deputy Chief on 6 February 1931 . He became Air Officer Commanding Wessex <unk> Area in February 1931 and then Air Officer Commanding Middle East Command in September 1931 . He then returned to the Air Ministry , where he became Air Member for Supply and Organisation on 14 January 1935 , during the beginnings of the pre @-@ war expansion and <unk> . He was advanced to Knight Commander of the Order of the Bath in the 1935 <unk> Honours and promoted to air marshal on 1 July 1935 . He attended the funeral of King George V in January 1936 . 
 <unk> , <unk> remained a close follower of Trenchard during the interwar period ; his time in the Independent <unk> Force had left him convinced that strategic bombing was an exceptionally powerful weapon , and one that could not effectively be defended against . In this , he was a supporter of the standard doctrine of the day , which suggested that the destructive power of a bomber force was sufficiently great that it could <unk> an industrial economy in short order , and that so merely its presence could potentially serve as an effective deterrent . He was promoted to air chief marshal on 1 April 1937 . 
 On 1 September 1937 , <unk> was appointed as Chief of the Air Staff , the military head of the RAF , in succession to Sir Edward Ellington . The promotion was unexpected ; of the prospective candidates <unk> for the job , <unk> has been widely seen by historians as the least gifted . The most prominent candidate was Hugh <unk> , the head of RAF Fighter Command and senior in rank to <unk> by three months , who had been informally told by Ellington in 1936 that he was expected to be appointed as the new Chief of the Air Staff . The decision was taken by the Air Minister , Viscount <unk> , without consulting Ellington for advice . 
 During 1936 and 1937 , the Air Staff had been fighting with the Cabinet over the <unk> plans ; the Air Staff wanted a substantial bomber force and only minor increases in fighters , whilst the Minister for Defence Co @-@ ordination , Sir Thomas <unk> , successfully pushed for a greater role for the fighter force . <unk> was promoted during the middle of this debate , and proved perhaps more flexible than might have been expected . In 1938 he supported sharp increases in aircraft production , including double @-@ shift working and <unk> of factories , and pushed for the creation of a dedicated organisation to repair and refit damaged aircraft . He supported expenditure on the new , heavily armed , Hurricane and Spitfire fighters , essential to re @-@ equip Fighter Command . He even began to distance himself , albeit slightly , from orthodox bomber philosophy , noting to the Minister for Air that " no one can say with absolute certainty that a nation can be knocked out from the air , because no @-@ one has yet attempted it " . Discussing plans for reacting to a war with Italy , in early 1939 , he opposed a French proposal to force Italy 's surrender by the use of heavy bombing raids against the north , arguing that it would be unlikely to force the country out of the war without the need for ground combat . 
 <unk> was advanced to Knight Grand Cross of the Order of the Bath in the 1938 <unk> Honours . He was still Chief of the Air Staff at the outbreak of the Second World War on 1 September 1939 ; his main contribution to the war effort was his successful resistance to the transfer of fighter squadrons to aid the collapsing French thus preserving a large portion of Fighter Command which would become crucial during the Battle of Britain . While he remained committed to the idea of a " knock @-@ out blow " offensive by <unk> Command , he also recognised that it was too weak to do so successfully , but still strongly opposed the use of the RAF for close air support . 
 He was promoted to Marshal of the Royal Air Force on 4 October 1940 and retired from the RAF later that month . He was awarded the Order of Merit on 29 October , and made a Knight Grand Cross of the Order of St Michael and St George on 21 November . 
 In February 1941 <unk> was appointed Governor @-@ General of New Zealand , a post he would hold for the remainder of the war . His time there was mostly quiet – described by one biographer as " a nice long rest " – and he toured the country extensively , referring to the war " in every public address " . <unk> and his wife , who also carried out an extensive program of engagements , were broadly popular , but there were occasional tensions ; shortly after his arrival , it was widely ( but mistakenly ) rumoured that he had slighted the " men " of the Army in favour of the " gentlemen " of the <unk> in a speech . A <unk> , <unk> became Grand Master of New Zealand 's Grand Lodge while Governor @-@ General . 
 A second conflict emerged just before the end of his term , when in 1945 , the Labour government sought to abolish the country <unk> , a system that gave additional electoral seats in rural areas . <unk> groups – predominantly National @-@ supporting – strongly opposed the move , and argued that such a major change could only be made after gaining approval in a general election . <unk> <unk> , and advised Fraser to wait until after the election , but did not feel it was appropriate to intervene ; he <unk> to the bill . 
 Following his return from New Zealand in 1946 , <unk> was raised to the peerage as Baron <unk> , of Clifton upon <unk> , in the county of Warwick . He spoke in the House of Lords rarely , making five speeches between 1946 and 1948 and one in 1959 , mostly addressing defence issues . <unk> died at his home at <unk> Street in London on 30 November 1963 , at which time his son Francis inherited his title . 
 Five crew <unk> took place over the station 's lifespan , in late 1977 @-@ early 1978 , late 1978 , mid @-@ 1979 , mid @-@ 1980 , and early 1981 , including <unk> from Warsaw Pact countries as part of the <unk> programme . These crews were responsible for carrying out the primary missions of <unk> 6 , including astronomy , Earth @-@ resources observations and the study of the effect of <unk> on the human body . Following the completion of these missions and the launch of its successor , <unk> 7 , <unk> 6 was <unk> on 29 July 1982 , almost five years after its launch . 
 The <unk> of the two ports was fitted with <unk> to allow the station to be <unk> by <unk> Progress spacecraft . These <unk> , which brought supplies and extra equipment to keep the station <unk> , helped ensure that the crew were always able to carry out useful scientific work aboard the station . In all , twelve Progress flights delivered over 20 tonnes of equipment , supplies and fuel . 
 <unk> 6 's propulsion system experienced a serious <unk> during the second crew <unk> in 1978 and was not usable again for the remainder of the station 's lifespan . As a consequence , it was limited to firing its attitude control <unk> and visiting spacecraft had to perform orbital adjustments . After each crew <unk> ended , it was necessary for Progress and <unk> spacecraft to boost the station into a high orbit so it wouldn 't decay until the next <unk> began . 
 The primary instrument carried aboard the station was the <unk> @-@ <unk> <unk> telescope , which could carry out astronomical observations in the infrared , ultraviolet and <unk> spectra using a 1 @.@ 5 metre @-@ diameter mirror which was operated in <unk> conditions at around − 269 ° C. The telescope could be operated only when <unk> 6 was on the night side of the Earth , and had its cover closed for the rest of the time . 
 The second major instrument was the <unk> @-@ <unk> <unk> camera , which carried out Earth @-@ resources observations . An improved form of a camera first tested on Soyuz 22 , the camera captured an area of 165 × 220 kilometres with each image , down to a resolution of 20 metres . Each image was captured simultaneously in six bands in 1200 @-@ frame <unk> , which required regular replacement due to the <unk> effects of radiation . <unk> 6 also featured a <unk> @-@ 140 stereoscopic topographic mapping camera with a focal length of 140 <unk> , which captured images of 450 × 450 kilometres with a resolution of 50 metres in the visible and infrared spectra , which could be operated either <unk> or by the resident crews . The photographic capabilities of the station were , therefore , extensive , and the Soviet Ministry of Agriculture had planted a number of specifically selected crops at test sites to examine the capabilities of the cameras . 
 To further expand its scientific capabilities , <unk> 6 was equipped with 20 <unk> for observations , two scientific <unk> to expose equipment to space or <unk> rubbish , and various pieces of apparatus to carry out biological experiments . Later on during the flight , a Progress spacecraft delivered an external telescope , the <unk> @-@ 10 radio observatory , which incorporated a directional antenna and five <unk> . The antenna was deployed on the rear <unk> assembly , with the controller remaining inside the station , and was used for both astronomical and meteorological observations . 
 <unk> 6 was primarily supported by the manned Soyuz spacecraft , which carried out crew <unk> and would also have been used in the event of an emergency evacuation . The ferries docked automatically to the station , making use of the new <unk> automatic <unk> system , and were used by departing crews to return to Earth at the end of their flight . 
 The station was the first to be able to be <unk> by the newly developed <unk> Progress <unk> , although they could only dock at the rear port , as the front port lacked the <unk> used to refuel the propulsion system . The <unk> docked automatically to the station via the <unk> , and were then opened and emptied by the <unk> on board , whilst transfer of fuel to the station took place automatically under supervision from the ground . 
